"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:6.7\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">6.7</span> Headdress, turban, hat</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">טְבוּל</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tvul)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek23:15\">EZK 23:15</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Aramaic</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">כַּרְבְּלָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(karbla’)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan3:21\">DAN 3:21</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מִצְנֶפֶת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mitsnefeth)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek21:31\">EZK 21:31</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">פְּאֵר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(p’er)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa3:20\">ISA 3:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek24:17\">EZK 24:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek24:23\">EZK 24:23</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צָנִיף</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tsanif)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job29:14\">JOB 29:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa3:23\">ISA 3:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa62:3\">ISA 62:3</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">κίδαρις</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kidaris)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Esd3:6\">1ES 3:6</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">πέτασος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(petasos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Macc4:12\">2MA 4:12</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0046_men_with_turbans.png\" alt=\"\n            \"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">\n             (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>The turban was a piece of material wrapped around the top of the head.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The cloth of the turban was wound around the upper part of the head several times and the end was tucked in. It may have been wound permanently and put on and taken off like a hat. See also <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">4.5.8 Turban, headdress&lt;REALIA:4.5.8&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In some languages there may be a very general word covering anything worn on the head. Where no more specific word exists for “turban,” this general word may be used for most of the references listed above. In some languages a descriptive phrase may be used, such as “covering made of cloth and wrapped around the head.”</p>\n<p>While some translations use words such as “hat” (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job29:14\">JOB 29:14</a> in <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr>) or “cap” (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan3:21\">DAN 3:21</a> in <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>), these words are generally used in English to refer to something more western than Bible characters would have worn. Terms like “turban” or “headdress” are more appropriate since they clearly refer to something less western. But this kind of distinction may be difficult to reflect in some languages that have only one term that refers to anything worn on the head. A possible model for “turban” in such languages is “special head covering.”</p>\n<p>For the translation of the Aramaic word <em>karbla’</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan3:21\">DAN 3:21</a>, see the comments at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">6.3 Shirt, tunic&lt;REALIA:6.3&gt;</a> “Shirt, tunic.”</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Macc4:12\">2MA 4:12</a> says literally “he induced the noblest of the young men to wear the Greek hat” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>). The hat in question was something worn by Greek athletes to identify with the god Hermes. Since this information is lacking for the modern reader, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr> has expanded this part of the verse to “he made the most outstanding of the young men adopt the hat worn by Greek athletes.” Some translations prefer to omit the hat and focus on the real issue that Jewish youth were being made to participate in forbidden Greek activities with their pagan associations; for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> has “[he] led our finest young men to adopt the Greek custom of participating in athletic events.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
